1. Make sure you’re on the right cluster

If you have multiple clusters, first be sure you’re talking to the one where ArgoCD should live:


kubectl config current-context
kubectl get ns



If needed:

aws eks update-kubeconfig --name <your-eks-name> --region <your-region>
aws eks update-kubeconfig --name 1988-dev-pipeline-eks88 --region us-east-1

2. Check if the ArgoCD CRD exists



kubectl get crd | grep applications.argoproj.io


If you see nothing → ArgoCD CRDs are missing → install ArgoCD (next step).

If you see a line → something else is wrong (but from your error, it’s almost surely missing).

3. Install ArgoCD on this cluster

Create the namespace (you already did, but it’s safe):



kubectl create namespace argocd || true



Install ArgoCD (CRDs + controller + UI):



kubectl apply -n argocd -f https://raw.githubusercontent.com/argoproj/argo-cd/stable/manifests/install.yaml



Wait for pods to be ready:

kubectl get pods -n argocd


You should see things like argocd-server, argocd-repo-server, argocd-application-controller, etc., in Running state.

4. Apply your Application again

Now re-apply your app manifest:

cd ~/Desktop/ALL-EKS-BACKUP/nginx-test-config/nginx-test-config/argocd/apps



kubectl apply -n argocd -f nginx-test-apps.yaml



Now it should succeed, and you can confirm:



kubectl get applications -n argocd



You should see:

nginx-test-helm-dev

nginx-test-kustomize-dev

listed as ArgoCD Application objects.



You’ve got ArgoCD running; now you just need a way to reach the UI.

You have two easy options:

quick & safe from your laptop only (port-forward)

public-ish via a LoadBalancer (EKS style)

Option 1 – Quick local access (port-forward)

Make sure ArgoCD server service exists:

kubectl get svc -n argocd
# you should see: argocd-server  ...  ClusterIP ...


Port-forward from your laptop:




kubectl port-forward svc/argocd-server -n argocd 8080:443




Leave that command running.

In your browser go to:




https://localhost:8080




(It’s https; you’ll get a self-signed cert warning, just accept/continue.)

Get the initial admin password:




kubectl -n argocd get secret argocd-initial-admin-secret \
  -o jsonpath="{.data.password}" | base64 -d; echo




username: admin

password: the value printed above

Option 2 – Expose via LoadBalancer (EKS)

If you want a public URL/IP from AWS:

Change the service type:



kubectl patch svc argocd-server -n argocd \
  -p '{"spec": {"type": "LoadBalancer"}}'


Get the external address:

kubectl get svc argocd-server -n argocd


Look for EXTERNAL-IP (or hostname).

Open in browser:

https://<EXTERNAL-IP or hostname>


Login with:

admin

password from the argocd-initial-admin-secret command above.

If you tell me which option you prefer, I can also help you add DNS (like argocd.yourdomain.com) and clean it up.